# TypeScript Standards for DotGitHub

## Code Style

- Use semicolons consistently
- Prefer explicit return types for public methods
- Use `interface` over `type` for object shapes when possible
- Use `const` assertions for immutable data structures

## Type Safety

- Always use strict TypeScript settings
- Prefer `unknown` over `any` when type is truly unknown
- Use branded types for IDs and paths to prevent mixing them up
- Use generic constraints to ensure type safety

## Imports and Exports

- Use ES modules with `.js` extensions in imports (TypeScript requirement)
- Prefer named exports over default exports for better tree-shaking
- Group imports: external packages first, then internal modules
- Use `export type` for type-only exports

## Error Handling

- Use Result types or throw specific error classes
- Include context in error messages
- Use JSDoc for complex error conditions

## Examples

```typescript
// Good: Explicit types and proper error handling
export interface ActionConfig {
  readonly name: string;
  readonly version: string;
}

export function createAction(config: ActionConfig): Result<Action, Error> {
  // Implementation
}
```